Fig. 3
 shows the electrical characteristics in a semi-log scale of the fabricated MIM devices. Fig. 3(a) shows the I–V measurement of the reference sample with the negligible hysteresis window. Meanwhile, the presence of significant I–V hysteresis window in NVM device as shown in Fig. 3(b) might be attributed to the charge storage capability correlated to the existing of GQDs in the device. For both devices, the applied voltage was swept from −2.0 to 2.5V and vice versa. For NVM device with the applied voltage varied from 0 to 2.5V, there was an abrupt increase in current at about 1.0V. It was the “ON” voltage (VON
) that switched the device from low- to high-current state. It remained at high-current state when voltage was sweeping back from 2.5 to 0V. Further decrease in voltage from 0 to −2V would change the applied polarity on the device. It was noticed that the device switched from high- to low-current state at −1.3V. The device maintained its low-current state even when the voltage was continued to sweep from −2 to 0V.

An endurance test for “write-read-erase-read” as shown in Fig. 4(a) was performed to observe the switching characteristics of the as-fabricated device. Fig. 4(b) and (c) illustrate the band diagram of the NVM device consistently and subsequently being programmed and erased with the 2.5 and −2.0V when the voltages were applied alternatively to the AgNWs electrode. The device is assumed as programmed when electrons are trapped in GQDs, and it is erased when electrons in GQDs are detrapped. In the program stage, the 2.5V pulse applied to the AgNWs electrode will inject electrons from ITO electrode into GQDs, as shown in Fig. 4(b). In the erase stage, the −2.0V pulse applied to the AgNWs electrode will attempt to eject the trapped electrons out of GQDs, as shown in Fig. 4(c). In Fig. 4(a), the programmed current (ION
                     ) and erased current (IOFF
                     ) are read with 0.5V applied to the AgNWs electrode; each cycle shows apparent differences to avoid false reading in ION
                      and IOFF
                      for a duration of 250s and the device demonstrated the switching behavior similar to rewritable flash memory,
